<a name="gary">
<center><h2><font size=+3>I</font>NSIDE <font size=+3>D.C.</font></h2></center>
<p><hr width=30% size=2><p>
<center><font size=+2><b><i>Looking for Lincoln</i></b></font><br>
by Gary L. Bauer</center>
<p>
<font size=+3>G</font>en. Colin L. Powell has declined to run for President in 
1996. He has also said that he will not accept the Vice Presidency, though 
time may change this decision. Finally, he is joining the Republican party. 
These are crucial decisions.
<p>
As everyone knows by now, Powell had described himself as 
&quot;pro-choice&quot; on abortion during an interview with ABC's 
Barbara Walters on the eve of his national book tour.  That position, 
combined with the warm reaction to his candidacy among some conservative
leaders in Washington, raised the real possibility that, for the first time 
in two decades, the Republican platform next year would reflect a 
&quot;pro-choice&quot; position on abortion.
<p>
The media response to this prospect, as well as to Powell, was
wild excitement.  From a strict news sense, it's not hard to understand why. 
A Powell candidacy presented historic opportunities: the nomination and 
possible election of the first black American President. Second, a GOP 
abandonment of its pro-life plank would have caused an earthquake
on the American political landscape.  Earthquakes are hard news.
<p>
The Republican Platform calls for a constitutional amendment to provide legal 
protection for the unborn.  It also calls for the appointment of judges who 
respect traditional values and the sanctity of innocent human life.  Has it 
made much difference?  One conservative leader has said that a pro-choice 
president like Powell &quot;could do more to lower the number of abortions 
than a presidential candidate who claims to be pro-life, who supports a 
constitutional amendment to ban abortions, but who does nothing more than pay 
lip-service to the pro-life constituency.&quot;
<p>
Of course, pro-life Americans want no part of this leader's dilemma.
 They prefer a third way: someone, Republican or Democratic, who not only claims 
to be, but is, pro-life, who supports full legal protection for the unborn, 
and who will pay service to that goal in both speech and action.
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
<center><i><font size=+2>PERSISTENCE ISN'T<br>
ALWAYS APPRECIATED.</font></i></center>
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
So why are pro-life Americans so often made to feel like skunks at the wedding 
party?  Partly, I'm sure, it's because nothing is more alien to the modern 
American mind than a moral absolute, even when that absolute is the 
overwhelming duty to refrain from taking innocent human life.  Second,
there is the matter of persistence.  It isn't always appreciated.
<p>
In his <i>Lincoln: The War Years</i>, Carl Sandburg retells the story
of a White House reception after Lincoln's Second Inaugural. Frederick 
Douglass, the black anti-slavery leader, tried to enter the White House 
to greet the President.  Guards barred his way.  Douglass eluded them 
and rushed through the door.  He was seized and escorted to a plank that
led outside through a window. Once again on the street, he asked a 
passerby entering the White House to tell Lincoln that &quot;Frederick 
Douglass is detained by officers at the door.&quot;
<p>
Hearing the news, Lincoln invited Douglass into the East Room, and the 
journalist finally greeted the reelected president.  Lincoln told Douglass 
that he had seen him in the crowd listening to his address. &quot;There 
is no man's opinion that I value more than yours,&quot; Lincoln told him, 
&quot;what do you think of it?&quot;  Douglass replied, &quot;Mr. Lincoln, 
it was a sacred effort.&quot;
<p>
In this world of slippery slope relativism, where rights to do
wrong are enshrined among our political commandments, the pro-life cause 
is often treated like an unwelcome guest.  As 1996 approaches, some of 
the political &quot;palace guards&quot; are already trying to show us to the 
window again.  As they do so, we could use a little of the spirit of
Frederick Douglass.  After all, this cause is a sacred effort, too.
<p><hr><p>
<a name="horizon">
<center><h2><font size=+3>O</font>N THE <font size=+3>H</font>ORIZON</h2></center>
<p><a name="hyde">
<li>Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) introduced constitutional amendment (H.J.
Res. 121) Nov. 16 to <b>restore full religious liberty and prevent discrimination 
against people of faith</b>. Proposed amendment reads:  &quot;Neither the United 
States nor any state shall deny benefits to or otherwise discriminate against 
any private person or group on account of religious expression, belief, or
identity; nor shall the prohibition on laws respecting an establishment
of religion be construed to require such discrimination.&quot; <b>Watch for 
congressional hearings in coming months</b>. If approved by <b>two-thirds 
majority vote in both chambers</b>, amendment will be submitted to state 
legislatures for ratification.
<p>
<li>Widespread sleaze on local cable channels at issue in <b>new case
accepted by U.S. Supreme Court</b> Nov. 13.  Case involves constitutional 
challenge to Helms Amendment to 1992 cable television law. <b>Amendment 
protects consumers from undesired indecent programming</b>. FRC will 
file/cosign legal brief to high court.  Watch for reports as <b><i>Alliance 
for Community Media v. F.C.C.</i> drama unfolds next year.</b>
<p>
FRC's &quot;Straight Talk,&quot; a weekly television program
on National Empowerment Television, is moving to a new satellite setting. The 
new setting is Galaxy 6, Transponder 7.  Does your cable carrier offer NET? 
If not, call us and we'll rush you a postcard you can mail to your local cable
operator requesting the network.  Our number is 1-800-225-4008.
Thank you.
<p><hr size=2><p>
