<p><hr><p>

<a name="dc">

<center>
<h2><font size=+3>I</font>NSIDE <font size=+3>D.C.</font></h2>
</center>

<p><hr width=30% size=2><p>

<center>
<font size=+2><b><i>Renewing Our Vows</i></b></font><br>
by Gary L. Bauer
</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>I</font>n announcing his support for the just-introduced 
federal Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA), Sen. Dan Coats of Indiana had
this to say:

<p>

&quot;The definition of marriage is not created by politicians
and judges, and it cannot be changed by them.  It is rooted in
our history, our laws, our deepest  moral and religious convictions,
and our nature as human beings.  It is the union of one man and
one woman.  This fact can be respected or it can be resented.
But it can't be altered.&quot;

<p>

If someone had told me five years ago that we would find
ourselves in 1996 defending marriage as the union of one man and
one woman, I would have asked him if he wanted me to take him
to my leader -- jokingly, of course.

<p>

Yet this idea of opening marriage to homosexual couples,
which seems more suited to another planet, is stalking the land.
Prompted by an impending court decision in Hawaii, legislators
in more than 30 states are rushing to protect their marriage statutes.
As of this writing, 11 states had enacted marriage protection
laws. 

<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>

<center><i><font size=+2>
ELEVEN STATES HAVE ACTED TO<br>
PROTECT MARRIAGE.
</font></i></center>

<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>

At the federal level, the Defense of Marriage Act was introduced
in the House on May 7 by Reps. Steve Largent (R-Okla.) and Bob
Barr (R-Ga.) and in the Senate on May 8 by Don Nickles (R-Okla.).
It is being endorsed by a slowly growing list of Congressional
sponsors, but many more are needed -- and swiftly, as the Supreme
Court decision in <I>Romer v. Evans</I> illustrates (<I>See</I> 
&quot;Courtwatch,&quot; page 3).

<p>

This is the most important pro-family legislation in many
years.  If marriage falls, it will begin a domino effect that
will totally redefine families within the law and culture.  For
starters, children will be taught in school that homosexuality
is the moral equivalent of marital love, businesses will be forced
to subsidize homosexual relationships, and churches that uphold
biblical morality will find themselves outside the civil law.

<p>

On Mother's Day, I debated Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) on
<I>This Week With David Brinkley.</I>  I reminded Mr. Frank that
it was fitting that we were discussing this on Mother's Day, since
our celebration of motherhood is one of the most powerful expressions
of just why the idea of homosexual &quot;marriage&quot; is so
dopey.  But it is more than dopey; it is dangerous.

<p>

If unelected judges in Hawaii are able to impose their will
on the rest of the nation through the Constitution's Full Faith
and Credit Clause (which compels the states to recognize each
other's licenses and records), then what's safe?  If two men can
marry, why can't three men?  Or two men and a woman?  Or a man
and a boy?

<p>

During our debate, Frank made the usual unfounded charge
that his opponents are motivated by &quot;hatred&quot; and 
&quot;prejudice.&quot; He repeated what has become homosexual activists' 
key argument against DOMA:  it is unnecessary.  Homosexual 
&quot;marriage&quot; is still illegal all over the U.S.  In other words, 
Barney Frank and friends want us to wait for a judicial defeat before we 
take the field in defense of marriage.  I'm sorry, but that's not good
enough. Marriage is the God-given foundation of society, and if
we let it be ruined, our children will rightly hold us responsible.

<p>

During the Battle of Britain, when things looked darkest,
Winston Churchill told the English people to &quot;never give
up.  Never, never, never, never give up.&quot;  Well, friends,
not only won't we give up defending marriage, we cannot give up.
I urge you to call or write your senators and congressman now
and press them to sponsor DOMA. Next Mother's Day, I don't
want to be debating a triumphant Barney Frank and his newly married
&quot;spouse.&quot;

<p><hr width=50%><p>

On May 19, the Family Research Council placed a full-page ad in 
<i>The Washington Post</i> with the tag line, "Let's Save Marriage, 
Before the Whole Cake Crumbles." The ad summarized the arguments for 
preserving the institution of marriage as a legally binding 
relationship between one man and one woman. <b>For a copy of the ad, 
or information about placing it in a local publication, call us at 
1-800-225-4008</b>.

<p><hr><p>

<a name="horizon">

<center>
<h2><font size=+3>O</font>N THE <font size=+3>H</font>ORIZON</h2>
</center>

<p>

<li>Pennsylvania faces <B>uproar over unauthorized physical exams</B>.
State Public School Code and the State Health Department require
physical examinations for girls in the sixth and 11th grades.
Sixth grade girls at the J. T. Lambert elementary school were
<B>subjected to genital exams without parental knowledge or permission.</B> 
Parents assert such exams, while not illegal, are inappropriate
without their prior permission.  With the promotion of &quot;school-based
clinics&quot; through programs like <B>Goals 2000, such incidents
could become commonplace.</B>  This and similar incidents <B>providing
momentum for Congressional parental rights bill</B> (<I>See</I>
cover story).

<p>

<li><B>Budget process for 1997 underway</B> in Congress.  Congressional
leaders still striving for many pro-family objectives that were
either <B>partially realized during past year or thwarted by Clinton
vetoes.</B>  On May 16, House passed a budget resolution calling
for balanced federal budget within six years, <B>permanent $500-per-child
tax credit,</B> termination of funding for the Arts (after fiscal
year 1997) and Humanities (after 1998) endowments, <B>elimination
of Legal Services Corporation in 1998, Surgeon General's Office,
and Goals 2000 education programs.</B>

<p>

Welfare reform, similar to plan vetoed by President
Clinton, <B>likely to be coupled with restraint
on growth in Medicaid spending.</B> Stand-alone tax package is
likely, featuring $500-per-child tax credit. <B>Pro-life gains
of 1995-96</B> (e.g., protecting teaching hospitals from abortion 
training mandates, preventing federally supported human embryo
experiments, overturning Clinton's mandate allowing
abortion in military hospitals) <B>are likely to survive.</B>

<p>

Dole's departure may <B>reduce slightly Senate Democrats'
inclination to filibuster</B> against unfinished items on pro-family 
agenda. However, continuing threat of presidential vetoes implies 
<B>hard-fought incremental progress</B>, rather than major policy
changes, this year. Welfare overhaul, long-term family
tax relief, and greater local and parental authority
over education likely to <B>meet Clinton veto pen head on.</B>

<p><hr size=2><p>

