<P><LI>Kus, Robert J. "Alcoholics Anonymous and Gay American Men." <I>Journal of Homosexuality</I> Vol. 14 No. 2, 1987: 
254.
<P><LI>"Gays Are More Prone to Substance Abuse."<I> Insight</I>  5 November 1990.
<P><LI>The following vignettes are a few of the many accounts received in personal letters by the 1993 Army Task Force, 
of which the author was a member, that studied homosexuality in military service. 
<P><LI>Baker, Stewart L. "Presidential Directive to Modify the Ban on Active Military Service by Homosexual Individuals: 
Implications for Military Preparedness and for Health Promotion in Our Scaled-Down Military Services." 
unpublished White Paper for the Society of Medical Consultants to the Armed Forces.  30 July 1993.
<P><LI>Ibid.
<P><LI>Kuchta, John C. "Psychiatry, Amendment 2 and Homosexuality." <I>Rocky Mountain GOLD</I> March 1993: 3.
<P><LI>Ibid.
<P><LI>Baker, op cit.
<P><LI>Juchta, op cit.
<P><LI>Schwartz, Mark F. and Masters, William H. "The Masters and Johnson Treatment Program for Dissatisfied 
Homosexual Men." <I>American Journal of Psychiatry</I> Vol. 141, No. 2, February 1984: 173-181.
<P><LI>"AMA Stops Backing Efforts to `Straighten Out' Gays." <I>The Washington Times</I> 22 December 1994: A-9.
<P><LI>Sarbin, Theodore R. and Karols, Kenneth E. "Nonconforming Sexual Orientations in the Military and Society." 
Defense Personnel Security Research and Education Center, Department of Defense, 1990.
<P><LI>Bell, Alan P. and Weinberg, Martin S.<I> Homosexualities: A Study of Diversity Among Men and Women</I>. (New York: Simon & Schuster, 1978): 426.
<P><LI>U.S. General Accounting Office, "Homosexuals in the Military: Policies and Practices of Foreign Countries," 
Washington, D.C., U.S. Government Printing Office, 1993, p. 3.
